    "84168105": {
      "title": "Future of milk fat modification by production or processing: Integration of nutrition, food science and animal science",
      "abstract": "Abstract Food components can be chemically or physiologically defined. Chemical definitions were more thoroughly understood when the USFDA published its first labeling regulations, and the chemical definitions of fats persist on food labels today. Advances in nutritional information reveal serious disparities between the two types of definitions. Clearly the consumers' expectations are not being met by the definitions behind the regulations in force today. For example, the chemical definitions of sub-groups, such as saturated fat, that are placed on food labels and the physiological implications of fat as understood by the consumer reading those labels are often seriously incompatible. Accurate information on food labels is the first issue that needs to be addressed so that consumers have the information needed to design diets that are consistent with a healthy lifestyle. A second issue is a method to motivate the consumer to use nutritional information. Both issues, accurate label information and behavior modification, have the full attention of competitive food industries."
    },
    "84168495": {
      "title": "Milk fat technologies and markets: A summary of the Wisconsin Milk Marketing Board 1988 Milk Fat Roundtable",
      "abstract": "Abstract The Wisconsin dairy industry has initiated development of a coordinated research program to increase the marketability of milk fat. In September 1988, the Wisconsin Milk Marketing Board invited 15 researchers from industry and academia to a milk fat round Table. This meeting had three goals: 1) to assess current technologies used to process milk fat; 2) to identify the technological needs for advanced milk fat manipulation; and 3) to determine the research priorities required to fulfill these needs. The round table identified research priorities for milk fat, calling for the development of research data in the following areas: milk fat ingredient functionality, milk fat fermentation, milk fat fractionation and cholesterol removal, milk fat health issues, control of milk fat composition, and economic data on milk fat derivatives."
    }
  },
